<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-914-182  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 914 182.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Nov 27 1989 v23 n48 p4(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Hungry like the capitalist wolf. (high-technology opportunities inEastern Europe)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Kornel, Amiel.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>US hardware and software firms are eyeing new businessopportunities in Eastern Europe as the Soviet Union and East Bloccountries continue to lift trade barriers.andP;  Analysts say that thegreatest need in these nations is distributed process controlsystems for agricultural and industrial use.andP;  Computers andsoftware are vital in the current policy of attempting to increaseWestern imports.andP;  The lifting of travel restrictions is alsolikely to increase the installed base of microcomputers asEastern-bloc systems purchase machines when visiting the West.andO;Hewlett-Packard says that its Eastern European business grew 58percent in FY 1989.andP;  Microsoft plans to re-evaluate its businessplan in the light of the recent reforms.andP;  Major hurdles includethe fear of political upheavals incited by revolutionary fever andthe Multilateral Coordinating Committee on Export Controls (Cocom)embargo list.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     International TradeMicrocomputersComputer industryHigh TechnologyEastern EuropeEuropeCommerceCoordinating Committee for Multilateral Export Controls.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>